<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_BasisMinimalSpanningSet"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Basis is minimal spanning set</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>If <math>
               <latex>V=\span(S)</latex>
            </math>, then <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> is a basis of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> if and only if removing any <math>
               <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
            </math> from <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> yields a set <math>
               <latex>S'</latex>
            </math> which fails to span <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>Consider first the case where <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is a basis of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. If we remove a vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> from <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>, we obtain a set  <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>  whose 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>span does not contain <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <crossref>
                     <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearIndependenceFacts"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Look up this fact</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </crossref>
               </subordinate>.
			Thus <math>
                  <latex>S'</latex>
               </math> fails to span  <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Conversely, suppose removing any vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> from <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> yields a set <math>
                  <latex>S'</latex>
               </math> which fails to span <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is linearly independent. We argue by contradiction: Suppose <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is linearly dependent. Then there is a vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> which is a linear combination of the remaining vectors in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. So form <math>
                  <latex>S'</latex>
               </math> by removing <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> from <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. We find <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)= \span(S')</latex>
               </math>, contradicting the assumption of the proposition.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>We have shown that the assumption that <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is not linearly independent leads to a contradiction to the hypothesis of this result. This assumption is, therefore, false. Consequently <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> a linearly independent spanning set of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>; i.e. it is a basis of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
